    ## Recent Methods and Advances
    
    **Real-to-Complex Conversion Approach (November 2025)**
    
    A novel method efficiently identifies zeros by tracking minima of |Z(t)|, achieving stability and precision up to t ≈ 10^20 with moderate computational cost, using AWS EC2 computation. This approach employs a real-to-complex number conversion and a novel valley scanner algorithm for evaluating Z(t) = eiθ(t)ζ(1/2 + it) at large imaginary parts t.
    
    **Valley Scanner Algorithm (December 2025)**
    
    A numerical framework replaces classical Gram-point bracketing with a real-to-complex parametrization of the critical line, and combined with high-precision evaluation of the Hardy Z function using the Riemann-Siegel formula, this parametrization induces a Valley Scanner algorithm that identifies local minima of the absolute value of Z and refines them using safeguarded Newton iterations.
    
    **Variational Approach (January 2026)**
    
    A novel variational numerical method for the theoretical investigation of the real zeros of the Hardy Z–function Z(t) was introduced, designed to circumvent certain limitations of classical approaches. This approach builds on an accelerated asymptotic formula for Z(t) established in earlier work, simplifying the structure of the error term and producing a family of tractable approximants.
    
    These methods represent significant improvements over traditional approaches by moving away from reliance on Gram points and classical Riemann-Siegel evaluations, with cloud-based implementations allowing computations at unprecedented heights along the critical line.
    
    
