    ## Recent Results (2025-2026)
    
    A 2025 paper "Transformers Provably Learn Chain-of-Thought Reasoning with Length Generalization" (Huang et al., November 2025) discusses the widely held conjecture that TC0 ≠ NC1 in circuit complexity theory. In November 2025, the ACL published work on "Circuit Complexity Bounds for RoPE-based Transformer Architecture", which establishes theorems conditional on the assumption that TC0 ≠ NC1.
    
    ## Counting Classes and TC0
    
    Researchers have defined the counting classes #NC1, GapNC1, PNC1 and C=NC1, and proved that boolean circuits, algebraic circuits, programs over nondeterministic finite automata, and programs over constant integer matrices yield equivalent definitions of the latter three classes.
    
    One significant result includes the unconditional separation of TC0 from the counting hierarchy, which represents an important finding regarding the relationships between TC0 and counting complexity classes.
    
    ## Open Problems
    
    Proving or refuting the strict separation TC0 ≠ NC1 remains a central open problem in circuit complexity with broad implications for parallel versus inherently sequential computation.
    
