    ## Background on the Maynard-Tao Sieve
    
    The breakthrough result of Zhang first established that there are bounded gaps between consecutive primes, and this was quickly followed by another extraordinary argument by Maynard (and discovered independently by Tao), establishing the existence of many primes in bounded intervals. In November 2013, James Maynard dramatically slashed this bound to 600, by a substantially easier method.
    
    ## Recent Progress and Applications
    
    The polymath project, with Maynard's assistance, eventually obtained the bound H₁ ≤ 246. More recent developments include work by Oxford mathematician James Maynard in 2020 (two years before he was awarded the Fields Medal), where he showed that the level of distribution is at least 0.6, beating the previous record of 0.57 from the 1980s for many commonly used sieves.
    
    ## Very Recent Results (2024-2026)
    
    Three of Maynard's graduate students have written papers extending both Maynard's and Zhang's results, with one paper by Jared Duker Lichtman pushing Maynard's level of distribution up to about 0.617.
    
    A recent paper applies modern analytic number theory tools – most notably, the Maynard sieve and recent correlation estimates for bounded multiplicative functions – to resolve problems on the prime counting function and its relatives.
    
    The search results show ongoing development in this field, though specific major breakthroughs from early 2026 aren't prominently featured in these results.
    
    
